WEBVTT

00:03.786 --> 00:04.178
.

00:04.221 --> 00:06.049
- Previously
on "Lincoln Rhyme"...

00:06.093 --> 00:07.442
- Agent Cutter.

00:07.485 --> 00:09.313
- So you're the dog
with the bone flooding my inbox

00:09.357 --> 00:12.055
every day with your thoughts?

00:12.099 --> 00:14.101
You're smart, and you're good,

00:14.144 --> 00:15.363
but if you can't play
on the team,

00:15.406 --> 00:17.147
you'll only be so good.

00:17.191 --> 00:18.801
- I read your file.

00:18.844 --> 00:20.063
Sounds like you're just putting
in the required three years

00:20.107 --> 00:21.325
so you can get in the FBI.

00:21.369 --> 00:23.284
Then what,
be a profiler?

00:23.327 --> 00:25.286
- The FBI rejected me.

00:25.329 --> 00:28.245
- This is... Jane.

00:29.333 --> 00:31.074
You're the bone collector.

00:31.118 --> 00:32.119
- I am.

00:33.729 --> 00:36.340
- You know that if you kill me,
it'll torture you.

00:36.384 --> 00:38.299
- I've been looking through
the files from Westchester.

00:38.342 --> 00:39.822
- Oh, my God.
You found something.

00:39.865 --> 00:41.737
- A victim who got away who
might still be alive.

00:41.780 --> 00:43.347
- You think it's
the Bone Collector?

00:43.391 --> 00:44.609
- I need that name.

00:44.653 --> 00:46.742
- Peter.

00:46.785 --> 00:49.484
Peter Taylor.
- I know him.

00:49.527 --> 00:52.530
[dramatic tone]

00:57.492 --> 01:02.540
- ♪ What to do now that she
doesn't want me ♪

01:03.802 --> 01:04.760
♪ That's what--

01:04.803 --> 01:06.370
[crash]

01:07.154 --> 01:09.765
- NYPD.
We have a search warrant.

01:12.246 --> 01:15.249
- ♪ What to do to keep
from being lonely ♪

01:15.292 --> 01:17.164
- Living room clear.

01:18.687 --> 01:20.689
- Peter Taylor,
show yourself.

01:21.777 --> 01:24.780
- ♪ What to do

01:26.608 --> 01:28.392
♪ The record hops

01:28.436 --> 01:32.396
♪ And all
the happy times we had ♪

01:32.440 --> 01:35.399
[tense music]

01:35.443 --> 01:39.577
♪

01:39.621 --> 01:42.754
- NYPD.
Show me your hands.

01:42.798 --> 01:44.452
- Careful.

01:44.495 --> 01:46.149
You know how he is with traps.

01:46.193 --> 01:53.200
♪

01:56.290 --> 01:59.815
- Oh, my God.
That's his wife.

02:00.946 --> 02:03.862
- Danielle Taylor,
maiden name Crocker.

02:05.821 --> 02:07.692
- Bastard killed his own wife.

02:08.780 --> 02:11.653
- We need a crime tech in here.
- No, we don't have time.

02:14.873 --> 02:17.398
This doesn't look like
his other kills.

02:19.965 --> 02:22.490
There's no sign of trauma.

02:25.014 --> 02:26.885
No blood.

02:26.929 --> 02:28.148
- Her hand.

02:38.375 --> 02:39.681
- [gasps]

02:42.901 --> 02:46.514
- Her ring finger--
he took out the bone.

02:48.690 --> 02:49.821
He wanted us to know

02:49.865 --> 02:52.737
this marriage
meant something to him.

02:52.781 --> 02:53.912
- Check the other hand.

02:55.784 --> 02:57.786
- [breathing heavily]

03:00.919 --> 03:02.312
Red fabric.

03:03.835 --> 03:06.011
Leather maybe,

03:06.055 --> 03:08.840
and some sort of residue
on her palm.

03:10.364 --> 03:13.367
[phone ringing]

03:16.326 --> 03:17.545
- It's coming from her body.

03:19.851 --> 03:21.288
- Have Sellitto answer it.

03:21.331 --> 03:22.332
I want to watch.

03:22.376 --> 03:25.379
[ringing continues]

03:43.353 --> 03:45.268
- We know who you are,
Peter Taylor.

03:46.617 --> 03:49.577
- Detective Sellitto,
it is you, isn't it,

03:49.620 --> 03:52.536
the man who put
his partner in danger?

03:52.580 --> 03:55.670
You let him go into that
warehouse three years ago

03:55.713 --> 03:57.715
without backups?
- You son of a--

03:57.759 --> 03:59.413
I want to talk
to Lincoln Rhyme.

04:01.110 --> 04:02.590
- Patch him through.

04:07.377 --> 04:08.639
Peter Taylor.

04:10.946 --> 04:14.384
- Lincoln Rhyme.

04:14.428 --> 04:16.778
We finally get
to play out in the open.

04:16.821 --> 04:20.042
- Your face is going to be
plastered all over the city.

04:20.085 --> 04:21.391
You won't be able to get
a cup of coffee

04:21.435 --> 04:23.393
without someone calling 911.

04:23.437 --> 04:25.787
- You don't know
what I'm capable of.

04:27.441 --> 04:30.400
I was under your nose
for years, right next to you,

04:30.444 --> 04:35.971
but the great Lincoln Rhyme
was too focused on himself,

04:36.014 --> 04:38.016
his book, his fame,

04:38.060 --> 04:41.672
to pay attention
to a lab tech like myself.

04:41.716 --> 04:43.500
- Trying to get his location.
Signal is scrambled.

04:43.544 --> 04:45.720
Keep him talking.
- Is that what this is about?

04:45.763 --> 04:47.025
Jealousy?

04:48.853 --> 04:50.942
- Gods suppressed
become devils.

04:50.986 --> 04:53.118
- So you consider
yourself a deity.

04:53.162 --> 04:56.121
- I consider myself
superior to you.

04:56.165 --> 04:57.297
- Really?

05:01.475 --> 05:04.478
Looks like you just killed
the one person who trusted you.

05:08.177 --> 05:12.703
- I spared her the madness
of what's to come.

05:12.747 --> 05:13.965
- You murdered her.

05:14.009 --> 05:15.445
- You're missing the point.

05:15.489 --> 05:17.447
- You delude yourself
that there is a point.

05:17.491 --> 05:19.536
There is only your psychopathy,
your insanity.

05:19.580 --> 05:21.582
- Now you're profiling,
Lincoln,

05:21.625 --> 05:23.627
which tells me I'm winning.

05:23.671 --> 05:25.020
You're grasping
at the academic

05:25.063 --> 05:28.763
because you have
nothing concrete to find me.

05:28.806 --> 05:30.895
- You overestimate yourself.

05:30.939 --> 05:33.376
- Now you're showing
your arrogance,

05:33.420 --> 05:36.553
your--your fatal flaw.

05:43.560 --> 05:46.128
There's a new game, Lincoln.

05:46.171 --> 05:48.391
You still have your clues,

05:48.435 --> 05:51.089
but I'm not stopping
at three bodies.

05:51.133 --> 05:56.051
I'm going to keep killing
so the world knows

05:56.094 --> 05:58.183
your insignificance.

05:58.227 --> 05:59.707
- We're going to stop you.

05:59.750 --> 06:02.492
- There, that's my point.

06:02.536 --> 06:05.365
You can't stop me.

06:10.065 --> 06:13.024
[foreboding music]

06:13.068 --> 06:16.071
♪

06:22.425 --> 06:22.599
.

06:22.643 --> 06:24.645
- Peter Taylor.
- A forensic tech.

06:24.688 --> 06:26.211
I barely knew he was there.

06:26.255 --> 06:30.390
- Well, he remembers you.
I need everything you have.

06:30.433 --> 06:32.130
I want the bone collector.

06:32.174 --> 06:34.350
- Not to put too fine
a point on it,

06:34.394 --> 06:36.874
but are you squeezing us out?

06:36.918 --> 06:40.356
- As Lincoln can tell you,
I believe in the team approach,

06:40.400 --> 06:42.402
something I'm happy
you've embraced.

06:42.445 --> 06:45.230
- A lot has changed since
we last saw each other.

06:46.014 --> 06:49.452
- I see that.
You look good, Lincoln.

06:49.496 --> 06:52.455
- So do you.
- Mm, even the gray hair?

06:52.499 --> 06:53.500
- Gives you character.

06:55.545 --> 06:57.417
- To answer Detective
Sellitto's question,

06:57.460 --> 06:59.201
we are not taking the case.

06:59.244 --> 07:02.073
We are working in step
on this for now.

07:02.117 --> 07:03.423
Talk to me.

07:03.466 --> 07:05.425
- Felix.

07:05.468 --> 07:07.644
- Peter Taylor.

07:07.688 --> 07:10.908
Date of birth
February 10th, 1968,

07:10.952 --> 07:13.041
Worked as a lab tech
with the NYPD

07:13.084 --> 07:16.000
from 2005 to 2017,

07:16.044 --> 07:18.394
married Danielle Crocker 2011.

07:18.438 --> 07:20.483
- Now his wife's
in the morgue downtown.

07:20.527 --> 07:23.094
- We have an arsenal of clues
on this one; we can stop him.

07:23.138 --> 07:26.968
- But looking at this report,
I may have something.

07:27.011 --> 07:29.927
- Amelia Sachs,
my eyes and ears

07:29.971 --> 07:32.234
and sometimes my second brain.

07:32.277 --> 07:34.628
- Agent Cutter, I'm actually
a huge fan of your work.

07:34.671 --> 07:36.717
I audited your forensic
psychology course.

07:36.760 --> 07:39.241
It changed the way
I thought about crime.

07:39.284 --> 07:41.243
- And did anything you learn
give you insight

07:41.286 --> 07:42.462
into our suspect?

07:42.505 --> 07:43.463
- It did.

07:46.161 --> 07:48.468
He married in 2011,

07:48.511 --> 07:51.558
started the Bone Collector
kills in 2012.

07:51.601 --> 07:54.561
This relationship anchored him.

07:54.604 --> 07:58.521
5 years, 15 murders,

07:58.565 --> 08:02.351
no mistakes,
then suddenly he stops.

08:02.394 --> 08:04.179
Why?

08:04.222 --> 08:06.311
The object of his competition,
Lincoln Rhyme,

08:06.355 --> 08:07.748
is no longer in the game.

08:07.791 --> 08:12.709
Then Lincoln comes back,
jolts the Bone Collector.

08:12.753 --> 08:16.017
He moves back to New York City,
starts making mistakes.

08:16.060 --> 08:19.063
He even...

08:19.107 --> 08:20.369
kills his wife.

08:20.412 --> 08:22.327
- Meaning what?
- Meaning that,

08:22.371 --> 08:25.113
while it's obvious
the Bone Collector

08:25.156 --> 08:26.331
is fixated on you,

08:26.375 --> 08:28.769
without his anchor,
he starts slipping.

08:28.812 --> 08:31.554
- Unless he finds a new anchor.

08:33.687 --> 08:36.690
- That's impressive,
Detective Sachs.

08:36.733 --> 08:39.083
- Officer.
- Then we find the next anchor.

08:39.127 --> 08:41.303
We have a location
on the parents, in-laws?

08:41.346 --> 08:42.522
- His parents are both
deceased.

08:42.565 --> 08:44.611
Danielle Crocker's parents
live in Queens.

08:44.654 --> 08:46.395
Uni is on the way
to notify them now.

08:46.438 --> 08:48.353
all: We're not putting
unis on this.

08:49.224 --> 08:53.576
- Sellitto, Danielle's parents,
not just a notification.

08:53.620 --> 08:55.622
We need to find out everything
they know about this guy

08:55.665 --> 08:57.319
and if they've seen him.

08:57.362 --> 08:59.495
- I'll send agents with you.
We share information.

08:59.539 --> 09:02.106
What I know, you know.
What you know, I know.

09:03.673 --> 09:07.024
If you ever think about
a career in profiling,

09:07.068 --> 09:08.199
give me a call.

09:32.876 --> 09:34.617
- [blows]

09:42.625 --> 09:46.194
- Clue number one:
goatskin leather, red dye.

09:46.237 --> 09:50.372
Nothing special except traces
of polytetrafluoroethylene,

09:50.415 --> 09:53.375
commonly known as Teflon,
on the underside.

09:53.418 --> 09:55.551
- Teflon.
- Bulletproof vest, maybe?

09:55.595 --> 09:57.379
- It doesn't seem dense enough
for a vest.

09:57.422 --> 09:58.815
- More likely waterproofing

09:58.859 --> 10:01.296
or possibly a Teflon tape
of some kind.

10:01.339 --> 10:04.821
What about the residue
on the wife's hand?

10:04.865 --> 10:07.737
- Clue two: epinephrine.

10:07.781 --> 10:09.870
- Adrenalin.

10:09.913 --> 10:11.654
Did the victim
have food allergies?

10:11.698 --> 10:13.090
- Working on medical records.

10:13.134 --> 10:14.831
- We didn't find any evidence
of it at the scene.

10:14.875 --> 10:17.573
There was no EpiPens,
no medications.

10:17.617 --> 10:19.401
- But it was highly diluted.

10:19.444 --> 10:21.098
I don't think we're dealing
with injectable adrenaline.

10:21.142 --> 10:23.579
- Teflon-coated leather...

10:23.623 --> 10:25.712
adrenalin...

10:25.755 --> 10:28.497
two clues, not enough.

10:28.540 --> 10:31.587
What's the third? Song?

10:31.631 --> 10:34.372
- That would be my bet.
He left it on repeat,

10:34.416 --> 10:36.461
which means
he wanted us to hear it.

10:36.505 --> 10:37.767
- Felix, pull it up.

10:42.554 --> 10:46.558
- ♪ What to do now that
she doesn't want me ♪

10:46.602 --> 10:50.214
- "What to Do" by Buddy Holly.
Lyrics mean anything?

10:51.607 --> 10:52.869
- Maybe it's not the lyrics.

10:52.913 --> 10:54.479
It was one of Holly's
final recordings

10:54.523 --> 10:57.482
he taped at his apartment
in Greenwich Village.

11:00.181 --> 11:03.793
- Goatskin leather, adrenaline,
Greenwich Village.

11:03.837 --> 11:06.622
[traffic sounds]

11:12.454 --> 11:13.673
Hard Times Boxing Gym.

11:15.805 --> 11:17.154
- Excuse me?

11:18.765 --> 11:19.896
- Red leather.

11:22.246 --> 11:23.508
From a boxing glove.

11:24.335 --> 11:26.294
They often contain Teflon.

11:26.337 --> 11:29.471
Adrenaline, used to treat cuts
during a fight.

11:29.514 --> 11:32.169
The song, recorded
in Greenwich Village,

11:32.213 --> 11:35.651
the location of Hard Times Gym,

11:35.695 --> 11:37.566
my gym from back in the day.

11:39.699 --> 11:40.830
These clues are about me.

11:40.874 --> 11:43.746
He's connecting them
to my past again.

11:43.790 --> 11:46.618
Amelia, I want you
and Eric there now.

11:46.662 --> 11:49.273
I'll have Cutter meet you.
Go.

11:51.754 --> 11:54.191
- Hey. What did Sellitto
get on Danielle's parents?

11:54.235 --> 11:56.585
- Nothing that helps us.

11:56.628 --> 11:58.413
- Never had a clue that Taylor
was anything other

11:58.456 --> 12:01.982
than a good guy,
good husband, go figure.

12:02.025 --> 12:04.375
- No one at NYPD
had any idea either.

12:04.419 --> 12:06.377
He compartmentalized.
- Yeah.

12:06.421 --> 12:08.292
Damn freak, he could just be
out here walking around

12:08.336 --> 12:09.337
like normal.

12:19.608 --> 12:20.696
- Look familiar?

12:20.740 --> 12:22.437
- 30 years,
the place hasn't changed.

12:22.480 --> 12:24.918
- Office clear.
- Spend a lot of time here?

12:24.961 --> 12:27.703
- Kept me off the street,
out of trouble.

12:27.747 --> 12:29.531
- You, trouble?

12:29.574 --> 12:31.228
- Oh, I have a past.

12:31.272 --> 12:32.795
- Locker room clear.

12:32.839 --> 12:34.754
- Love to hear
about it sometime.

12:39.584 --> 12:40.585
- [gasps]

12:43.414 --> 12:44.764
Lincoln...

12:51.683 --> 12:52.684
- Cutter.

12:52.728 --> 12:55.687
[dark music]

12:55.731 --> 12:57.733
♪

13:02.520 --> 13:02.869
.

13:02.912 --> 13:05.872
- [gasping]
I never saw him.

13:05.915 --> 13:09.136
[shivering]
I... I didn't see him.

13:09.179 --> 13:11.878
Someone brushed against me,

13:11.921 --> 13:14.402
and I woke up here, like this.

13:15.490 --> 13:17.013
- It's okay.
- No, no, no.

13:17.057 --> 13:18.014
- We're gonna get you out.
- No, no, no!

13:18.058 --> 13:19.059
- Wait.

13:21.931 --> 13:24.760
He set up a motion sensor.

13:24.804 --> 13:27.197
The pipes are rigged to burst
if you come too close.

13:27.241 --> 13:28.895
or I stand up.

13:28.938 --> 13:30.461
The steam will cook you alive.

13:30.505 --> 13:32.159
- We have to do something!

13:32.202 --> 13:35.031
- It's a stomach wound.
She's bleeding out.

13:35.075 --> 13:37.904
We can't.
She's in bad shape, okay?

13:37.947 --> 13:40.341
I can't let you put yourself
in harm's way.

13:42.430 --> 13:44.867
- Okay.
We just need to figure out

13:44.911 --> 13:48.958
what he wants us to do
and do the opposite.

13:49.002 --> 13:50.830
- It's too late.

13:50.873 --> 13:52.962
It's too late.
This is a no-win situation.

13:53.006 --> 13:54.311
- Amelia, I know
what you're thinking,

13:54.355 --> 13:56.270
but even if you figure it out,
we can't save her.

13:56.313 --> 13:57.880
- We just need to find where
the sensors are

13:57.924 --> 13:58.968
and disable them.

13:59.012 --> 14:00.535
- Amelia, no,
it's too dangerous!

14:00.578 --> 14:02.145
- Lincoln Rhyme would
find another way.

14:02.189 --> 14:03.538
- Lincoln Rhyme ended up
paralyzed

14:03.581 --> 14:04.887
looking for another way.

14:04.931 --> 14:06.410
- Well, he's not invincible,
Lincoln, okay?

14:06.454 --> 14:08.195
Peter Taylor is not
invincible.

14:08.238 --> 14:09.892
We can do this.

14:09.936 --> 14:14.505
- Amelia, I've been doing this
a long time.

14:14.549 --> 14:16.420
You have to know

14:16.464 --> 14:21.077
what part's bravery
and what part's futility.

14:21.121 --> 14:23.427
- I am not giving up.

14:23.471 --> 14:25.081
She is not gonna die.

14:25.125 --> 14:27.040
- No, we can't, Amelia.
We can't. We can't!

14:27.083 --> 14:28.345
That will kill you.

14:28.389 --> 14:29.433
- I'll be damned if I'm going
to let him do

14:29.477 --> 14:31.131
to you what he did to Linc--

14:31.174 --> 14:33.916
[screaming]

14:33.960 --> 14:36.092
- Amelia!

14:36.136 --> 14:39.139
[screaming]

14:44.492 --> 14:46.494
[shrieking]

14:50.454 --> 14:53.414
[somber music]

14:53.457 --> 15:00.464
♪

15:04.512 --> 15:05.861
- Amelia.

15:10.344 --> 15:12.172
- Watching someone die...

15:15.349 --> 15:18.961
Someone I knew...

15:19.005 --> 15:21.224
someone I looked up to.

15:21.268 --> 15:23.096
- Hey.

15:23.139 --> 15:24.488
- I know.

15:24.532 --> 15:27.535
I know we don't have time
for emotion right now.

15:27.578 --> 15:29.972
I have to put it aside
until this is done.

15:30.016 --> 15:31.931
- I'm not putting
my emotions aside.

15:35.151 --> 15:36.326
- No?

15:36.370 --> 15:37.545
- Hell no.

15:39.068 --> 15:41.984
I'm angry.
I'm furious.

15:42.028 --> 15:45.596
So if you want to be sad,
be sad.

15:45.640 --> 15:47.947
Let it fuel you.

15:49.383 --> 15:53.300
If you want to be mad,
let it motivate you.

15:56.042 --> 15:57.347
- [scoffs]

16:00.263 --> 16:02.048
Yeah, I like that.

16:03.223 --> 16:05.616
The Bone Collector
won't know what's coming.

16:09.098 --> 16:12.014
- One more thing.

16:12.058 --> 16:14.625
I'm no longer
calling him that,

16:14.669 --> 16:17.628
the self-anointed,
self-important title.

16:19.413 --> 16:21.241
You know who he really is?

16:23.069 --> 16:26.072
Peter Taylor,

16:26.115 --> 16:29.379
the small man
behind the big name.

16:29.423 --> 16:30.990
We're going
to make sure he pays

16:31.033 --> 16:32.339
for what he just did to Cutter.

16:34.036 --> 16:36.038
- For what he did
to all of them.

16:36.082 --> 16:37.039
- Mm.

16:37.083 --> 16:40.042
[dramatic music crescendos]

16:40.086 --> 16:47.093
♪

16:49.747 --> 16:51.749
- Three clues left
at the boxing gym.

16:51.793 --> 16:53.229
Here's number one.

16:53.273 --> 16:55.275
It's an electronic key card
of some kind.

16:55.318 --> 16:57.581
It's not your standard hotel
one as far as I can tell,

16:57.625 --> 16:59.235
which might work in our favor

16:59.279 --> 17:01.585
'cause it could make it easier
to narrow down.

17:01.629 --> 17:03.109
- Which you're doing right now?

17:03.152 --> 17:05.154
- I just wanted to keep you
in the loop.

17:05.198 --> 17:07.591
Which I'm doing right now.
I'll do a deeper dive.

17:07.635 --> 17:10.594
- Clues two and three
are a pair.

17:12.509 --> 17:14.511
I'm so sorry.
I should've cropped that.

17:14.555 --> 17:19.516
- No, I need to see everything.

17:19.560 --> 17:21.736
Keep going.

17:21.779 --> 17:23.259
- A flower petal.

17:23.303 --> 17:25.522
I am running the DNA through
a horticultural database.

17:25.566 --> 17:28.047
- Flower DNA?
- All living things.

17:28.090 --> 17:29.700
- What's near the petal?

17:29.744 --> 17:33.530
- Water and wheat flour, maybe
from a flatbread or a cracker.

17:33.574 --> 17:35.793
- So he's literally
leaving us bread crumbs.

17:35.837 --> 17:37.317
- And all I can tell you
right now

17:37.360 --> 17:39.449
is that there's some sort
of imprint on it,

17:39.493 --> 17:40.755
maybe a letter I.

17:40.798 --> 17:42.409
- I'm working the image.

17:42.452 --> 17:45.455
I'll try to enhance it
once I run down the key card.

17:45.499 --> 17:46.630
- Lincoln.

17:49.242 --> 17:51.113
- Claire, what's the matter?

17:51.157 --> 17:54.421
- It's Naia and Camden.
- What's wrong?

17:54.464 --> 17:55.509
- They're here.

17:57.163 --> 17:59.165
- Surprise!

17:59.208 --> 18:00.688
- Hi.

18:03.386 --> 18:06.302
- You changed everything
in here.

18:06.346 --> 18:08.304
It's like a high-tech Batcave.

18:08.348 --> 18:11.742
- I thought you'd be past
your Batman phase by now.

18:11.786 --> 18:13.701
- I'm in my Steph Curry phase.

18:13.744 --> 18:16.269
I can do
the two-handed dribble.

18:16.312 --> 18:18.401
- His team had a tournament.

18:18.445 --> 18:20.664
Steph Curry here
wanted to surprise you.

18:20.708 --> 18:22.666
- Well, I'm surprised.

18:22.710 --> 18:26.061
Camden, do you want to give
your mom and I a minute?

18:26.105 --> 18:28.672
Claire keeps the fridge
stocked, plenty of good stuff.

18:39.640 --> 18:41.294
- What's going on?

18:41.337 --> 18:42.860
- We ID'd the Bone Collector
last night.

18:42.904 --> 18:45.211
You didn't see anything?
- Oh, God.

18:45.254 --> 18:49.302
We got to the airport at 8:00.
I've been in airplane mode.

18:49.345 --> 18:51.869
I...

18:51.913 --> 18:53.654
who is he?

18:53.697 --> 18:54.829
- He was a forensic specialist.

18:54.872 --> 18:56.396
We were in
the academy together.

18:56.439 --> 18:59.225
- You knew him?
- He was...

18:59.268 --> 19:02.532
innocuous, forgettable,

19:02.576 --> 19:05.883
but still, I should have--
- What?

19:05.927 --> 19:08.408
- Found him, caught him,
put him away.

19:08.451 --> 19:12.151
He just killed an FBI agent.
He killed his wife.

19:12.194 --> 19:14.240
This time, he's not stopping
until I catch him.

19:14.283 --> 19:16.546
- Or until he catches you.

19:22.770 --> 19:25.729
- What you're really looking
for is in the drawer.

19:25.773 --> 19:27.688
- Sellitto's not gonna
like that.

19:27.731 --> 19:32.171
- Hm, yeah, well, don't tell
anyone I told you.

19:33.259 --> 19:34.738
- His kettle corn, you have it?

19:34.782 --> 19:37.611
- Oh, yeah.
Legendary, right?

19:44.835 --> 19:47.925
Hey, let's you and I
get out of here.

19:47.969 --> 19:49.840
There's not enough to share.

19:55.803 --> 19:57.935
- Get Naia and Camden
to a safe house.

19:57.979 --> 20:01.548
Set up the best team you know.
No one gets in.

20:01.591 --> 20:03.376
No one gets out.

20:03.419 --> 20:06.509
- I'll do you one better.
I'll stay there myself.

20:08.555 --> 20:09.860
- Sellitto's new partner?

20:09.904 --> 20:12.689
- Detective Eric Castillo,
ma'am.

20:12.733 --> 20:16.258
Bone Collector isn't gonna get
anywhere near your family.

20:16.302 --> 20:17.477
Whenever you're ready.

20:21.611 --> 20:24.571
[somber music]

20:24.614 --> 20:31.621
♪

21:39.689 --> 21:41.256
- [inhales]

22:04.584 --> 22:07.282
- Camden, here's the deal.

22:07.326 --> 22:08.936
I'm going to be
honest with you.

22:10.372 --> 22:12.374
The Bone Collector
is back in New York.

22:12.418 --> 22:15.029
He's coming after me,
and I'm going after him.

22:17.901 --> 22:18.946
You scared?

22:21.470 --> 22:22.776
Me too.

22:24.952 --> 22:27.955
- But my money's on you.

22:31.959 --> 22:32.960
- I love you.

22:42.056 --> 22:43.840
I'll see you when this is over.

22:49.455 --> 22:52.109
We've had time; we need
to figure out the three clues.

22:52.153 --> 22:53.589
Key card?

22:53.633 --> 22:54.938
- Here's what I found.
The magnetic strip tell us

22:54.982 --> 22:57.593
the card
is manufactured by NPC, Inc.,

22:57.637 --> 22:59.116
National Plastic Cards.

22:59.160 --> 23:01.423
The type is the NPC 42.

23:01.467 --> 23:03.425
Three dozen hotels
in the area that use it.

23:03.469 --> 23:05.384
- Kate, please tell us
we're closer

23:05.427 --> 23:07.951
on the breadcrumbs.
- We are.

23:07.995 --> 23:11.520
The imprint wasn't
the letter I.

23:11.564 --> 23:13.000
It was this.

23:13.043 --> 23:15.611
- A communion wafer.
- And according to the imprint,

23:15.655 --> 23:17.439
this specific one was made
at a cloistered monastery

23:17.483 --> 23:18.745
in Philadelphia.

23:18.788 --> 23:20.137
- Well, he's not sending us
to Philadelphia.

23:20.181 --> 23:21.965
What's the flour?

23:23.140 --> 23:25.534
- A peony, a white peony.

23:28.668 --> 23:29.973
- You know what it means.

23:30.017 --> 23:32.498
- It's not the monastery.

23:32.541 --> 23:33.890
It's the church where you
take communion

23:33.934 --> 23:34.978
at a Catholic wedding

23:35.022 --> 23:37.067
but have the reception
at a hotel.

23:38.765 --> 23:40.462
If you check that list,
you're going to find

23:40.506 --> 23:42.899
the Marcy Hotel
across the river in Jersey

23:42.943 --> 23:45.467
uses the NPC 42 key card.

23:46.990 --> 23:49.123
The peony is a flower
often used in boutonnieres,

23:49.166 --> 23:52.735
which I know because I wore one

23:52.779 --> 23:54.389
at Sellitto's last wedding,

23:54.433 --> 23:55.999
where I was best man.

23:56.913 --> 23:59.133
I had him check the house
where Peter Taylor grew up.

23:59.176 --> 24:01.091
He should have
been back by now.

24:06.096 --> 24:07.794
- No answer.

24:07.837 --> 24:10.971
I got to move.
- Take the key card.

24:11.014 --> 24:12.581
Whatever it's for
at the Marcy Hotel,

24:12.625 --> 24:13.930
that's where you'll find him.

24:13.974 --> 24:16.672
- [whispers] Okay.

24:16.716 --> 24:19.675
[suspenseful music]

24:19.719 --> 24:26.726
♪

24:39.695 --> 24:40.087
.

24:40.130 --> 24:44.526
- NYPD--I need you to tell me
which room this card opens.

24:44.570 --> 24:46.485
Now!

24:46.528 --> 24:48.225
Come on, come on.

24:49.575 --> 24:51.011
- It's not for
any of the guest rooms.

24:51.054 --> 24:52.578
It's for roof access
for maintenance.

24:52.621 --> 24:54.014
- Thank you.

24:54.057 --> 24:55.145
Let's move!

24:57.104 --> 24:59.498
I'm on the roof.
- All right. Find him.

24:59.541 --> 25:03.327
- Sellitto! Sellitto!
I don't see him.

25:03.371 --> 25:06.983
- He has to be up there.
Amelia, watch every step.

25:08.115 --> 25:09.595
- I see him!

25:09.638 --> 25:11.031
- Oh, God, no.

25:11.074 --> 25:12.467
- Carefully.
- Move fast.

25:12.511 --> 25:16.471
- Sellitto!
- Amelia, wait! Dammit.

25:17.559 --> 25:19.343
- Careful.

25:19.387 --> 25:22.042
- What do you expect?
You trained her.

25:22.085 --> 25:24.087
- He's breathing.
I need some help over here.

25:28.265 --> 25:30.964
[blade slices]
- Got you. Okay.

25:31.007 --> 25:32.226
Got him.

25:32.269 --> 25:33.662
Okay, breathe.

25:33.706 --> 25:36.056
Okay.

25:37.623 --> 25:39.581
- I think he wanted me
to swallow that.

25:41.714 --> 25:43.454
- You okay?

25:45.239 --> 25:49.504
- Um, all things considered,
no, but...

25:49.548 --> 25:53.464
there are more important
things at the moment:

25:53.508 --> 25:55.379
clues.

25:55.423 --> 25:56.598
Things, you know...

25:56.642 --> 25:58.078
- We need to get
you checked out.

25:58.121 --> 25:59.122
- I'm okay.

26:01.124 --> 26:03.126
Just give me a minute.

26:03.170 --> 26:06.129
[dark music]

26:06.173 --> 26:13.180
♪

26:14.790 --> 26:19.316
- Are you seeing this?
- What is that, a--a mirror?

26:19.360 --> 26:22.015
- Whatever it is, bring it
back here with the casing.

26:27.803 --> 26:29.283
- We still need to find
the third clue.

26:29.326 --> 26:30.676
- There may not be one.

26:30.719 --> 26:32.503
Sellitto is still alive;
there was nothing rigged

26:32.547 --> 26:34.288
to take you down
when you found him.

26:34.331 --> 26:35.637
- Do you think
we interrupted him?

26:35.681 --> 26:37.073
- Maybe he had a camera
in the lobby

26:37.117 --> 26:40.120
and saw you coming in
or heard you,

26:40.163 --> 26:43.645
but knowing him, no way
he'd leave Sellitto alive.

26:48.171 --> 26:49.695
- Hey, are you okay?

26:49.738 --> 26:51.522
What are you doing here alone,
Sellitto?

26:54.613 --> 26:56.440
- I let him down.

26:56.484 --> 26:58.747
- Sellitto, you were drugged
and kidnapped.

26:58.791 --> 27:00.488
It's not your fault.

27:00.531 --> 27:02.664
- Sure it is.
I let it happen.

27:02.708 --> 27:03.970
- What are you talking about?

27:04.013 --> 27:06.189
- Ever since the
Bone Collector's been back,

27:06.233 --> 27:10.324
it's been about Lincoln:
his book, his professor.

27:10.367 --> 27:12.152
You heard the call
this morning.

27:12.195 --> 27:13.240
- I know.
- So we all know

27:13.283 --> 27:15.329
that puts
a target on our backs.

27:15.372 --> 27:17.636
You, you send Rachel
out of town.

27:17.679 --> 27:20.377
Camden and Naia
are in lockdown,

27:20.421 --> 27:24.164
and me,
I didn't see him coming.

27:24.207 --> 27:26.340
- You said he was hiding
in the back of your car.

27:26.383 --> 27:28.516
- Yeah, I had just checked out
his old house.

27:28.559 --> 27:32.259
I got back in the car.
I went to turn on the ignition.

27:32.302 --> 27:34.174
I felt a sting
in the back of my neck,

27:34.217 --> 27:37.481
and that's all I remember
until I woke up on the roof

27:37.525 --> 27:39.266
with your flashlight
in my face.

27:39.309 --> 27:41.181
- Again, not your fault.
Come on. Come on.

27:41.224 --> 27:42.356
- I put us all in danger

27:42.399 --> 27:44.097
because I let that son
of a bitch

27:44.140 --> 27:48.623
get the better of me,
and that will not happen again.

27:52.845 --> 27:55.064
- He didn't talk to you,
taunt you?

27:55.108 --> 27:56.457
Taunt you?

27:57.458 --> 27:59.460
- After the car,
everything went black.

28:00.635 --> 28:03.725
Claire, you don't have to
take care of me. I'm fine.

28:03.769 --> 28:07.642
- Lincoln's worried.
I help you, I'm helping him,

28:07.686 --> 28:11.341
and in case you're wondering,
Camden took your kettle corn.

28:11.385 --> 28:13.343
- [chuckles]
- Thank you.

28:13.387 --> 28:15.215
Look, I wish I had more.

28:15.258 --> 28:18.305
I wish Kate found trace.
I wish I knew the third clue,

28:18.348 --> 28:21.264
but I have
nothing else to offer.

28:21.308 --> 28:23.310
We have to work
from what we have:

28:23.353 --> 28:25.181
the casing and the metal plate.

28:25.225 --> 28:27.749
- It's a daguerreotype.
- A what?

28:27.793 --> 28:32.406
- A primitive photograph,
a process invented in 1839,

28:32.449 --> 28:35.148
a photo developed on
a silver-plated copper surface

28:35.191 --> 28:39.326
sensitized with iodine and
exposure to a mercury vapor.

28:39.369 --> 28:42.111
- So what's the picture?
- Felix is working on that.

28:42.155 --> 28:47.160
- I always wanted to do this.
- Glad someone's having fun.

28:47.203 --> 28:50.424
- We're exposing the plate
to mercury fumes,

28:50.467 --> 28:52.382
and I have to fix the image

28:52.426 --> 28:53.862
in a sodium
thiosulfate solution.

28:53.906 --> 28:56.256
Otherwise, it will disappear.

28:56.299 --> 28:59.563
- Thanks for the primer.
Trying to work the casing here.

28:59.607 --> 29:02.262
- Anything?
- Nine millimeter Parabellum.

29:02.305 --> 29:05.308
Striations say it was fired
from a Glock 17,

29:05.352 --> 29:09.486
residue says sometime
within the last 12 hours.

29:09.530 --> 29:12.141
- Anything on Sellitto's clues?

29:12.185 --> 29:15.579
- No trace I can pinpoint
to the Bone Collector,

29:15.623 --> 29:17.407
and we still don't have
a third clue.

29:17.451 --> 29:19.845
I'm not sure how it works
if we only have two.

29:21.411 --> 29:22.761
- Maybe a little heat.

29:30.551 --> 29:34.903
And as Monsieur Daguerre
himself might say, "Voila."

29:37.471 --> 29:40.779
I'm running an image search,
see if we can identify them.

29:41.518 --> 29:46.306
- Stephen A. Halsey, noted
fur trader from the mid-1800s.

29:50.919 --> 29:51.920
- Go on.

29:54.009 --> 29:58.318
- Halsey also famously sold
his land to John Jacob Astor,

29:58.361 --> 30:00.450
the wealthiest man in America
at the time.

30:02.539 --> 30:06.195
It became what is now known
as Astoria, New York.

30:06.239 --> 30:07.544
- Astoria.

30:09.938 --> 30:13.550
Okay.
So we have the location.

30:13.594 --> 30:15.857
- And with the shell, we have
a possible murder weapon.

30:15.901 --> 30:18.338
The problem is
we don't have a third clue.

30:18.381 --> 30:20.688
[cup and saucer rattling]

30:23.299 --> 30:25.475
- Still
a little shaken up is all.

30:25.519 --> 30:28.827
- Amelia, get Sellitto
to the nearest emergency room.

30:28.870 --> 30:30.785
- I'm telling you,
you're overreacting, Lincoln.

30:30.829 --> 30:32.874
- And I'm telling you,
it's like what you said.

30:32.918 --> 30:34.876
You don't exactly know
what happened from the time

30:34.920 --> 30:37.661
you were taken
to the time you woke up.

30:37.705 --> 30:39.750
He injected you with something.

30:39.794 --> 30:41.535
It's also possible
there was something else

30:41.578 --> 30:43.929
in the shell casing
besides just a bullet.

30:45.844 --> 30:48.020
If we all know Peter Taylor,

30:48.063 --> 30:51.414
I don't think we interrupted
him before his third clue.

30:55.723 --> 30:58.857
It's you.
You're the third clue.

31:05.733 --> 31:07.735
- Look, I'm fine, Amelia.
Just take me home.

31:07.778 --> 31:09.606
[mumbling]
- Sellitto, shut up. Sit down.

31:13.741 --> 31:15.047
NYPD emergency,

31:15.090 --> 31:16.700
I need a doctor,
and I need them now.

31:16.744 --> 31:18.485
- What's the problem?
- No, it's not for me.

31:18.528 --> 31:19.703
It's for him.

31:19.747 --> 31:21.749
- [shivering]

31:22.793 --> 31:23.969
- Sellitto?

31:26.493 --> 31:28.016
Oh, my God.

31:28.060 --> 31:30.410
We need a doctor, now!

31:30.453 --> 31:31.846
- Doc!

31:31.890 --> 31:33.761
Sir, sir!
Can you hear me?

31:33.804 --> 31:35.458
- What do we got?
- Unresponsive.

31:35.502 --> 31:36.807
[overlapping chatter]

31:44.337 --> 31:44.554
.

31:44.598 --> 31:47.470
[soft dramatic music]

31:47.514 --> 31:52.084
♪

31:52.127 --> 31:53.346
- What's his status?

31:57.089 --> 31:59.482
Don't look so surprised.

31:59.526 --> 32:00.919
He's my partner
eight years.

32:00.962 --> 32:02.094
You think I'm not
coming down here

32:02.137 --> 32:03.834
to tell him
to wake the hell up?

32:03.878 --> 32:05.227
- He, uh...

32:05.271 --> 32:07.273
he's stable for now.

32:10.102 --> 32:12.234
Lincoln, they still
don't know what it is.

32:12.278 --> 32:19.285
♪

32:31.036 --> 32:32.559
- I hate hospitals.

32:35.997 --> 32:38.260
When I was...

32:38.304 --> 32:40.610
injured,

32:40.654 --> 32:43.091
I was in a bed like this
for an eternity.

32:46.051 --> 32:48.923
They told me I had visitors,
but I turned them away.

32:51.012 --> 32:52.535
Sellitto kept coming back
no matter

32:52.579 --> 32:56.104
how many times I told him no.

32:56.148 --> 32:57.410
I think he thought I didn't
want him there

32:57.453 --> 33:00.848
because I blamed him.

33:00.891 --> 33:02.545
But that wasn't it.

33:04.678 --> 33:07.202
I was angry I couldn't be
what I used to be.

33:10.684 --> 33:12.425
Three years, I felt that way.

33:15.341 --> 33:18.039
He kept coming,

33:18.083 --> 33:21.869
kept trying...

33:21.912 --> 33:25.003
and finally,
he brought me you.

33:25.046 --> 33:28.049
- Well, he needed you.

33:31.574 --> 33:33.272
And you needed him.

33:37.363 --> 33:40.192
- Coming here, I realize
why he kept coming.

33:42.194 --> 33:44.022
It's not guilt, but pity.

33:48.200 --> 33:49.549
It's friendship.

33:54.336 --> 33:56.512
I'm here to give him mine.

33:56.556 --> 33:58.514
- I think you should
tell him that.

34:03.650 --> 34:05.043
- I just did.

34:08.350 --> 34:09.699
- How is Eric taking it?

34:09.743 --> 34:12.659
- [chuckles]
He knows we've got this.

34:12.702 --> 34:15.357
Said he has a job to do.

34:15.401 --> 34:17.359
He's not going
to leave my family.

34:19.405 --> 34:22.016
- Atropa belladonna.
- That's the poison?

34:22.060 --> 34:24.105
- And they can treat it.
They're on their way.

34:24.149 --> 34:25.498
I lit a fire.

34:30.416 --> 34:34.202
- Okay, so it's a plant
with highly toxic berries.

34:34.246 --> 34:38.119
- And quite a tradition of use
in murders and assassinations.

34:38.163 --> 34:40.034
- He--he's gonna be okay.

34:40.078 --> 34:42.210
- They're treating him
with physostigmine now,

34:42.254 --> 34:44.343
which has its
own complications, but--

34:44.386 --> 34:46.040
- But he's strong,
he's pig-headed,

34:46.084 --> 34:49.261
and he will not let the--
Peter win.

34:51.132 --> 34:53.134
- Okay, so we have
the third clue:

34:53.178 --> 34:55.223
belladonna,
somewhere in Astoria,

34:55.267 --> 34:57.225
and a shell casing
from a Glock 17.

35:01.273 --> 35:02.361
- I don't know.

35:04.276 --> 35:06.016
- Okay, think.

35:06.060 --> 35:11.283
This is about you,
so just let your mind drift.

35:11.326 --> 35:12.588
It'll come to you.

35:12.632 --> 35:14.460
- I know that.
I just...

35:17.550 --> 35:19.465
Belladonna,
I'm drawing a blank.

35:22.032 --> 35:24.034
A- I've got your journal here,
so let's--

35:24.078 --> 35:25.558
let's work it through.

35:25.601 --> 35:28.213
Has a long history of use
as a poison.

35:28.256 --> 35:29.388
Ancient Roman warriors would

35:29.431 --> 35:31.477
apply it
to the tips of their arrows.

35:34.132 --> 35:35.481
- Macbeth used belladonna
to poison

35:35.524 --> 35:37.744
the troops of Harold Harefoot,

35:37.787 --> 35:43.097
King of England, forcing them
to retreat to their ships.

35:43.141 --> 35:47.101
- It's used in medicines,
in cosmetics, in eye drops.

35:47.145 --> 35:49.364
Women used to use it to dilate
the pupils of their eyes

35:49.408 --> 35:51.236
so they could appear
more seductive.

35:51.279 --> 35:53.020
- Belladonna, it's also
referred to

35:53.063 --> 35:54.326
as deadly nightshade.

35:54.369 --> 35:56.719
It's a perennial
herbaceous plant.

35:56.763 --> 35:59.157
- Wait, what's it called?

36:00.201 --> 36:02.508
- Nightshade,
deadly nightshade.

36:02.551 --> 36:03.770
Why?

36:03.813 --> 36:06.033
- You know what it is.
- I know what it is.

36:07.556 --> 36:09.428
I know where it is,
and I know who.

36:09.471 --> 36:11.560
- Amelia?
- The Night Shade Cafe

36:11.604 --> 36:14.172
in Astoria--

36:14.215 --> 36:17.305
it's the new name of the diner
where my parents were killed

36:17.349 --> 36:20.743
with a 9-millimeter
round fired by a Glock 17.

36:20.787 --> 36:22.180
- That makes no sense.
It's indicating you.

36:22.223 --> 36:23.311
You're right here.

36:23.355 --> 36:24.443
- I know,
and I just called Rachel.

36:24.486 --> 36:27.315
She's safe, but I'm going.

36:27.359 --> 36:28.751
- The hell you are.
He's targeting you.

36:28.795 --> 36:30.318
- Taunting us, yes,

36:30.362 --> 36:32.190
but what I know is
that there's someone out there,

36:32.233 --> 36:34.496
someone out there that I can
save if I get there in time,

36:34.540 --> 36:35.845
just like we saved Sellitto,

36:35.889 --> 36:38.196
just like we saved
that woman at Grand Central.

36:38.239 --> 36:39.240
- You're not going.

36:39.284 --> 36:40.459
- Sellitto is out
of commission,

36:40.502 --> 36:42.374
and Eric isn't
leaving your family.

36:42.417 --> 36:44.680
Lincoln, I need your eyes
and ears

36:44.724 --> 36:46.552
in that cafe
to end this once for all.

36:46.595 --> 36:47.640
- The ESU--

36:47.683 --> 36:49.337
- The ESU could destroy
evidence

36:49.381 --> 36:50.730
if they go in there alone.
That's what you always tell me.

36:50.773 --> 36:52.819
- The answer is no.

36:52.862 --> 36:55.082
- I am not asking you, Lincoln.

36:55.125 --> 36:59.304
Whoever he has there tied up
or poisoned

36:59.347 --> 37:01.871
or clinging to life,

37:01.915 --> 37:03.612
I can stop it,

37:03.656 --> 37:07.268
and I can stop another person
from dying in that damn diner.

37:15.189 --> 37:15.537
.

37:15.581 --> 37:18.279
[helicopters whirring]

37:18.323 --> 37:21.282
[sirens wailing]

37:22.327 --> 37:24.067
- You need to talk her
through this, Lincoln.

37:24.111 --> 37:25.678
- I couldn't talk her
out of it.

37:25.721 --> 37:26.940
You think I can talk her
through it?

37:26.983 --> 37:29.899
- Yes, I do.
She's waiting for it.

37:31.336 --> 37:34.600
- Amelia, all that this place
means to you,

37:34.643 --> 37:36.689
everything it represents,

37:36.732 --> 37:38.734
you need to put it away now.

37:41.084 --> 37:44.174
- I'm fine.
- No, you're not fine,

37:44.218 --> 37:46.133
but you can do this.

37:46.176 --> 37:48.048
- All right.
Okay.

37:49.789 --> 37:52.748
It's just another...

37:52.792 --> 37:54.272
restaurant.

37:54.315 --> 37:57.231
[tense music]

37:57.275 --> 38:00.887
♪

38:00.930 --> 38:03.759
- The restaurant where the Bone
Collector may have laid a trap,

38:03.803 --> 38:05.718
so you are to hang back
and let ESU do their job.

38:05.761 --> 38:06.980
- Yes, sir.

38:07.023 --> 38:08.068
- If we see something
to help, fine.

38:08.111 --> 38:09.287
No chances, no risks.

38:09.330 --> 38:11.898
- Kitchen's clear.
- Bathroom's clear.

38:11.941 --> 38:12.986
- Amelia.

38:19.340 --> 38:20.907
Amelia.

38:20.950 --> 38:22.778
- All right,
show me the room.

38:25.390 --> 38:28.218
- Okay.

38:28.262 --> 38:30.830
- What do you see?
Just let me see it.

38:30.873 --> 38:32.266
- Okay.

38:33.398 --> 38:36.357
- Amelia,
stay with me on this.

38:36.401 --> 38:38.272
But if this is about you,

38:38.316 --> 38:41.754
tell me what's the same,
what's different.

38:43.146 --> 38:44.626
- The layout.

38:46.193 --> 38:47.629
This is it.

38:53.461 --> 38:57.030
The decor, everything,
it's--it's Lasky's.

38:57.073 --> 38:58.292
- Okay.

38:58.336 --> 39:01.861
Now, where did it happen?
- Lincoln.

39:01.904 --> 39:03.906
- He's brought you here
for a reason.

39:09.347 --> 39:10.652
Where did it happen?

39:13.829 --> 39:15.657
- It was right here.

39:21.837 --> 39:25.145
Julie, she was coming
to our table.

39:27.234 --> 39:30.890
She was smiling at me.
Then she brought us the check.

39:34.067 --> 39:39.942
Whitehead came in,
and when he called her name,

39:39.986 --> 39:40.987
she turned...

39:44.469 --> 39:45.687
And he shot her.

39:49.299 --> 39:52.433
My father stood up

39:52.477 --> 39:55.871
and tried to stop it,
and he shot him.

40:02.443 --> 40:05.707
And my mother leaned in
to shield me...

40:05.751 --> 40:08.449
[dramatic music crescendos]

40:08.493 --> 40:12.192
♪

40:12.235 --> 40:13.889
- [indistinct shouting]

40:15.413 --> 40:18.851
And she got shot.
It was here.

40:18.894 --> 40:21.984
[solemn music]

40:22.028 --> 40:29.035
♪

40:31.211 --> 40:33.431
He shot them right here.

40:33.474 --> 40:35.389
- There's something on that
smoke alarm right there.

40:35.433 --> 40:36.738
- Tell her not to move!

40:36.782 --> 40:38.305
- Wait, don't move!

40:38.914 --> 40:41.090
- I felt something when
I stood on the booth.

40:41.917 --> 40:43.919
- Can you see what it is?
- Tell her to get out of there.

40:43.963 --> 40:46.487
- Amelia.
- It's the job, Lincoln.

40:46.531 --> 40:48.446
You would do it
if you were here.

40:49.925 --> 40:51.405
Now work with me.

40:53.233 --> 40:54.234
Don't move.

40:57.150 --> 40:58.891
- What is it?

40:58.934 --> 41:02.982
- It's a trigger,
a wire going down.

41:03.025 --> 41:04.287
Here, help me get this up.

41:06.376 --> 41:07.856
Device!

41:07.900 --> 41:10.206
Set a perimeter!
Don't let anyone else out!

41:13.079 --> 41:14.428
[device ticking]

41:16.125 --> 41:18.780
- What is it?
- What it is is the same device

41:18.824 --> 41:20.303
from the warehouse
the day I fell.

41:20.347 --> 41:22.828
- Well, what is it?
Why didn't the dogs smell it?

41:22.871 --> 41:25.265
- The dogs have to be trained
for each substance.

41:25.308 --> 41:28.007
A-234 is a Russian
nerve agent, Novichok.

41:28.050 --> 41:30.792
- Lincoln, you know
what this is.

41:30.836 --> 41:34.579
You did it before,
and you know how to disarm it.

41:34.622 --> 41:36.058
Tell me what you did.

41:36.102 --> 41:37.538
- I pulled the white wire.
- That just means--

41:37.582 --> 41:39.235
- That means we don't know.

41:39.279 --> 41:40.585
He knows I know
that stopped him then,

41:40.628 --> 41:42.195
so is it the red wire
this time,

41:42.238 --> 41:43.631
the green one,
or would he think

41:43.675 --> 41:45.938
I think it's the other wires,
so it's white again?

41:45.981 --> 41:47.853
Or is it neither?
Well, you stop it,

41:47.896 --> 41:49.550
and the floor falls out
from under you.

41:49.594 --> 41:53.119
- We have to make a choice.
She can't stand here forever.

41:53.162 --> 41:54.555
- Lincoln.
- Not now, Claire!

41:54.599 --> 41:57.340
- This is exactly your problem,
Lincoln.

41:57.384 --> 42:00.343
[ominous music]

42:00.387 --> 42:07.350
♪

42:09.570 --> 42:13.008
You're always looking for me,
but you never really see me.
